r=rss&amp;emc=rss" /><description>The country on Thursday released a national artificial intelligence strategy that focuses on building its sovereign capability and protecting consumers.</description><dc:creator>Vjosa Isai</dc:creator><pubDate>Thu, 04 Jun 2026 19:56:41 GMT</pubDate><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Canada</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Mark Carney</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Artificial intelligence</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Jobs</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Consumer protection</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Privacy</category><media:content url="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2026/06/04/multimedia/04int-canada-ai-vqlh/04int-canada-ai-vqlh-videoSixteenByNineJumbo1600.jpg" medium="image"><media:credit>Chris Young/The Canadian Press, via Associated Press</media:credit><media:description>Prime Minister Mark Carney of Canada during a demonstration at a Toronto hospital on Thursday. “Canadian A.I. adoption will be prudent, pragmatic and pro-worker,” he said.</media:description></media:content></item><item><title>SpaceX Has $30 Billion Deal to Provide Google With A.I. Computing Power</title><link>https://www.nytimes.com/2026/06/05/technology/spacex-google-deal.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</link><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.nytimes.com/2026/06/05/technology/spacex-google-deal.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</guid><atom:link rel="standout" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2026/06/05/technology/spacex-google-deal.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss" /><description>Elon Musk’s rocket company said Google would pay it $920 million a month, as it prepared for its initial public offering.</description><dc:creator>Kate Conger</dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 06 Jun 2026 00:44:15 GMT</pubDate><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Space</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Computers and the Internet</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Tech Industry</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Artificial intelligence</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Google</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">SpaceX</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Elon Musk</category><media:content url="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2026/06/05/multimedia/05biz-spacex-google-qzjh/05biz-spacex-google-qzjh-videoSixteenByNineJumbo1600.jpg" medium="image"><media:credit>Carlos Barria/Reuters</media:credit><media:description>SpaceX’s Starbase offices in Texas. The agreement with Google could help to establish SpaceX as an infrastructure provider for companies that are fiercely competing in the A.I. race.</media:description></media:content></item><item><title>Why the SpaceX IPO Will Affect Your 401(k), Like It or Not</title><link>https://www.nytimes.com/2026/06/05/technology/spacex-indexes-401k.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</link><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.nytimes.com/2026/06/05/technology/spacex-indexes-401k.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</guid><atom:link rel="standout" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2026/06/05/technology/spacex-indexes-401k.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss" /><description>Elon Musk’s rocket company, on the cusp of the largest initial public offering ever, will soon end up in index funds after rule changes by Nasdaq and other index providers.</description><dc:creator>Mike Isaac and Maureen Farrell</dc:creator><pubDate>Fri, 05 Jun 2026 14:17:19 GMT</pubDate><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Stocks</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Bonds</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Private spaceflight</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">SP 500</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Space</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Pensions and Retirement Plans</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Nasdaq Composite</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Artificial intelligence</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Startup</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">IPO</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Indexers</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">SpaceX</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">NASDAQ OMX Group</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Standard &amp; Poor's</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Elon Musk</category><media:content url="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2026/06/04/business/00spacex-risk/00spacex-risk-videoSixteenByNineJumbo1600.jpg" medium="image"><media:credit>Olivier Heiligers</media:credit></media:content></item><item><title>Gwynne Shotwell, Elon Musk’s No. 2 at SpaceX, Is the Company’s Steady Hand</title><link>https://www.nytimes.com/2026/06/04/technology/gwynne-shotwell-spacex.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</link><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.nytimes.com/2026/06/04/technology/gwynne-shotwell-spacex.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</guid><atom:link rel="standout" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2026/06/04/technology/gwynne-shotwell-spacex.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss" /><description>Gwynne Shotwell, the president and chief operating officer, is the adult-in-the-room foil to Mr. Musk as SpaceX prepares for a blockbuster initial public offering.</description><dc:creator>Ryan Mac</dc:creator><pubDate>Thu, 04 Jun 2026 14:08:29 GMT</pubDate><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Gwynne Shotwell</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">SpaceX</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Elon Musk</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Women and Girls</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Private spaceflight</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Satellite</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Space</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Artificial intelligence</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Starlink</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Personal Profile</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">People Story</category><media:content url="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2026/06/01/business/00Biz-Shotwell-SUB/00Biz-Shotwell-SUB-videoSixteenByNineJumbo1600.jpg" medium="image"><media:credit>Joe Raedle/Getty Images</media:credit><media:description>Gwynne Shotwell, SpaceX’s president and chief operating officer, in Miami Beach last year during one of her infrequent public appearances. “I love working for Elon,” she has said.</media:description></media:content></item></channel></rss>